tactic where an adversary enumerates information about the environment (such as users, systems, resources, etc.)
basic queries against AD for users, groups, OUs, GPOs, etc. can help with lateral movement 

domain enumeration tools leverage LDAP or LDAPS, or newly ADWS (Active Directory Web Services) which wrpas LDAP queries in HTTP requests

bloodhound is great for graphing and visualizing, running bloodhood we are likely to get caught
  so best approach is to collect the data, convert to bloodhound format, and use bloodhound to graph
      collection: ldapsearch, pyldapsearch
      convert: BOFHound (https://github.com/coffeegist/bofhound)

LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol)
  389 (LDAP) or 636 (LDAPS)
  to search for objects using LDAP, we must provide a filter 
    e.g. to search for all USER accounts, ldapsearch (samAccountType=805306368)
  to further filter a search, we can add & or | operators
    e.g. to search for all USER accounts, with admin count of 1, and excluded krbtgt account, ldapsearch (&(samAccountType=805306368)(adminCount=1)(!(name=krbtgt)))
  to only return specific attributes, we can use the --attributes parameter
    e.g. if we only want name and group memberships, --attributes name,memberof
  NOTE: we can get the security descriptor of an object by appending ntsecuritydescriptor to our attributes parameter
        e.g. to return every attribute and the security descriptor, use *,ntsecuritydescriptor
  good to know LDAP queries:
    enumerating important details of every user, ldapsearch (samAccountType=805306368) --attributes samaccounttype,distinguishedname,objectsid,serviceprincipalname,useraccountcontrol,ntsecuritydescriptor
    query to find kerberoastable users: ldapsearch (&(samAccountType=805306368)(servicePrincipalName=*)(!samAccountName=krbtgt)(!(UserAccountControl:1.2.840.113556.1.4.803:=2)))
  OPSEC considerations with LDAP queries:
    be cautious with extremely large pulls, such as (objectClass=*)
    be cautious with search time, limit attributes to bare essentials (e.g. samaccounttype,distinguishedname,objectsid,ntsecuritydescriptor)
    be cautious with ineffecient searches (less than 10% of searched objects returned) 
